HomeWork 2- Titanic: Machine Learning from disaster¶

submmit: Iris Grabov & Shay Gelbart

https://www.kaggle.com/irisgrabov

About the task:

The Titanic dataset task is a foundational machine learning problem where you predict the survival of passengers aboard the Titanic based on provided features such as age, gender, ticket class, family relationships, and fare. The training dataset includes the "Survived" column (the target variable), which indicates whether a passenger survived (1) or not (0). Using this data, you train a machine learning model to make predictions. The test dataset does not include the survival outcomes, so our goal is to use the trained model to predict the survival for these passengers.

Heres a list of key concepts and tools we used:

  1. Data Preprocessing:

    • Categorical Encoding: One-Hot Encoding.
    • Handling Missing Values: Imputation.
    • Feature Selection: Identifying relevant features, removing redundant ones. Using RFE and RFECV
    • Conducted Hybrid feature selection
    • Forward selection
    • Backward elimination

  2. Feature Normalization:

    • Scaling: StandardScaler for feature normalization.
    • Regularization: Elastic Net, L1 and L2 penalties.

Bootstrap Aggregation: Resampled training data in 50 iterations to train the KNN and NBC model and averaged predictions for an ensemble effect.

  1. Modeling:

    • Logistic Regression: as requred in the work
    • Pipeline: Combining encoding, scaling, and model fitting.

  2. Metrics and Evaluation:

    • Confusion Matrix: For training and validation.
    • Classification Metrics: Precision, Recall, F1 Score, Accuracy, Specificity, FPR.
    • Balanced Accuracy.
    • Log Loss: For model performance comparison on incremental training sizes.

  3. Data Splitting:

    • Train-Test Split: 80% training, 20% validation.
    • Cross-validation (Learning Curve): Incremental training size evaluation.

  4. Competition Result:

    - Best Real Test Score: 0.77511.¶

    LDA- explain and investitation

KNN with Bootstrap: Achieved a public leaderboard score of 0.77511, ranking 7409th in the competition. What we did in part 2: KNN NBC LDA Bootstrapping Forward Feature Selection Backward Feature Selection Hybrid Feature Selection

These were the key components we used in your process!

the columns:¶

  • survival: Survival status (0 = No, 1 = Yes).
  • pclass: Ticket class (1 = 1st, 2 = 2nd, 3 = 3rd).
  • sex: Gender of the passenger.
  • age: Age in years.
  • sibsp: Number of siblings/spouses aboard the Titanic.
  • parch: Number of parents/children aboard the Titanic.
  • ticket: Ticket number.
  • fare: Passenger fare.
  • cabin: Cabin number.
  • embarked: Port of embarkation (C = Cherbourg, Q = Queenstown, S = Southampton).
  • name
  • passenger ID

We have to put attention to the values of each features. For example: we have the target 'Survived' with the values of 1 and 0, but we have to pay attention that this is a categotical target!

The analysis of missing values reveals the following:

  • Cabin has the highest number of missing values (687), with 77.1% of its data missing.
  • Age is the second most affected, with 19.9% of its values missing (177 entries).
  • Embarked has very few missing values (2), accounting for 0.22% of its data.
  • Other columns, such as PassengerId, Survived, Pclass, Name, Sex, SibSp, Parch, and Ticket, have no missing values.

This indicates that imputing or handling missing values is critical for Cabin, Age and Embarked.

  1. Cabin (77.1% missing): Drop the column: Since such a large proportion of data is missing, it might be best to drop this column.

  2. age: fill with the mean

  3. Embarked: fill with the most frequent value

def create_pie_chart_of_count(df, column_name):
    df_not_null = df[~df[column_name].isnull()]
    fig = px.pie(df_not_null.groupby([column_name]).size().reset_index(name='count'), names=column_name, values='count')
    fig.show()

The results show a significant difference in survival rates between genders on the Titanic:

  • 74.2% of women survived, indicating a much higher survival likelihood for women.
  • 18.9% of men survived, showing a significantly lower survival rate for men.

This reflects the "women and children first" policy often associated with maritime disasters.

def visualize_feature_relationship(data, column, target='Survived'):
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
    # Determine data type of the column
    if data[column].dtype == 'object' or data[column].nunique() < 10:  # Categorical columns
        sns.countplot(data=data, x=column, hue=target, palette='viridis')
        plt.title(f'{column} vs {target}')
        plt.xlabel(column)
        plt.ylabel('Count')
        plt.legend(title=target)
    else:  # Numerical columns
        sns.kdeplot(data=data, x=column, hue=target, fill=True, palette='viridis', alpha=0.5)
        plt.title(f'{column} Distribution by {target}')
        plt.xlabel(column)
        plt.ylabel('Density')
    plt.show()

HeatMap¶

def plot_correlation_heatmap(data, numeric_columns, title="Correlation Heatmap"):
    # Select numeric features only
    
    # Compute the correlation matrix
    correlation_matrix = numeric_columns.corr()
    
    # Plot the heatmap
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
    sns.heatmap(correlation_matrix, annot=True, fmt=".2f", cmap="coolwarm", cbar=True, square=True)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.show()

Pay attention: Correlation only captures linear relationships. Non-linear dependencies between features and the target won't be reflected. For example, a quadratic or other non-linear relationship may show little to no correlation but still be predictive.

therefore, we should take the result of the correlation matrix with a grain of salt.

# Define numerical and categorical columns
numerical_cols = X.select_dtypes(include=['int64', 'float64']).columns  # numeric features
categorical_cols = X.select_dtypes(include=['object', 'bool']).columns  # categorical features

# Define the ColumnTransformer with OneHotEncoder for both 'Sex' and 'Embarked'
ct_enc_std = ColumnTransformer([
    ('onehot_embarked', OneHotEncoder(), ['Embarked']),  # One-hot encode 'Embarked'
    ('onehot_sex', OneHotEncoder(), ['Sex']),  # One-hot encode 'Sex'
    ('standard', StandardScaler(), numerical_cols)  # Standardize numerical features
])

# Fit the ColumnTransformer on the data
ct_enc_std.fit(X)
# Create a DataFrame with the correct column names after transformation
onehot_embarked_feature_names = ct_enc_std.named_transformers_['onehot_embarked'].get_feature_names_out(['Embarked'])
onehot_sex_feature_names = ct_enc_std.named_transformers_['onehot_sex'].get_feature_names_out(['Sex'])
numeric_feature_names = numerical_cols.tolist()

# Combine all feature names into one list
all_feature_names = list(onehot_embarked_feature_names) + list(onehot_sex_feature_names) + numeric_feature_names

# Transform the data and create a new DataFrame
X_transformed = ct_enc_std.transform(X)
X_encoded = pd.DataFrame(X_transformed, columns=all_feature_names)

Checks if the dataset meets the requirements for LDA:¶

Limitations: Assumes that data for each class is normally distributed. Assumes that all classes have the same variance (homoscedasticity). Struggles with non-linear class boundaries

In [85]:
from scipy.stats import shapiro
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd

def check_lda_requirements(X, y):
    """
    Checks if the dataset meets the requirements for LDA.
    """
    issues = []

    # Check 1: Labels are discrete
    if not pd.Series(y).dtype.name.startswith("int"):
        issues.append("Target labels must be discrete (categorical).")
    else:
        print("Labels are discrete (categorical).")

    # Check 2: At least two classes
    if len(np.unique(y)) < 2:
        issues.append("Dataset must have at least two distinct classes in the target labels.")
    else:
        print("At least two distinct classes found.")

    # Check 3: Sufficient samples
    n_samples, n_features = X.shape
    if n_samples <= n_features + 1:
        issues.append(f"Insufficient samples. Need more than {n_features + 1} samples for {n_features} features.")
    else:
        print(f"Sufficient samples. {n_samples} samples found.")

    # Check 4: Normal distribution of features
    X = X.to_numpy() if isinstance(X, pd.DataFrame) else X
    for i in range(X.shape[1]):
        stat, p_value = shapiro(X[:, i])
        if p_value <= 0.05:
            issues.append(f"Feature {i+1} does not follow a normal distribution.")
        else:
            print(f"Feature {i+1} follows a normal distribution (p-value = {p_value:.4f}).")

    # Check 5: Shared covariance assumption (Box's M Test)
    try:
        cov_matrix = []
        for class_value in np.unique(y):
            X_class = X[y == class_value]
            cov_matrix.append(np.cov(X_class, rowvar=False))
        
        # Check if covariance matrices for different classes are similar
        if len(set([cov_matrix[i].shape for i in range(len(cov_matrix))])) > 1:
            issues.append("Covariance matrices for the classes are not similar. Box's M Test failed.")
        else:
            print("Covariance matrices are similar across classes.")
    except Exception as e:
        issues.append(f"Error in covariance check: {str(e)}")

    # Check 6: Low multicollinearity
    correlation_matrix = np.corrcoef(X.T)
    if np.any(np.abs(correlation_matrix[np.triu_indices_from(correlation_matrix, 1)]) > 0.9):
        issues.append("Highly correlated features detected (correlation > 0.9).")
    else:
        print("No highly correlated features detected.")

    # Check 7: Features with low variance
    if np.any(np.var(X, axis=0) < 1e-5):
        issues.append("Some features have very low variance (near constant).")
    else:
        print("No features with very low variance detected.")

    # Check 8: Balanced dataset
    class_counts = pd.Series(y).value_counts()
    imbalance_ratio = class_counts.max() / class_counts.min()
    if imbalance_ratio > 5:
        issues.append("Class imbalance detected. Imbalance ratio exceeds 5:1.")
    else:
        print(f"Class balance is acceptable. Imbalance ratio: {imbalance_ratio:.2f}.")

    # Final decision
    if issues:
        print("\nThe dataset is NOT suitable for LDA. Issues found:")
        for issue in issues:
            print(f"- {issue}")
        return False
    else:
        print("\nThe dataset is suitable for LDA.")
        return True

The usage of LDA¶

The output of the check_lda_requirements function indicates that while certain prerequisites for Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA) are met, the dataset is not suitable for LDA due to significant violations of key assumptions. Specifically, the dataset satisfies the requirements of having discrete target labels, sufficient samples (891 samples for 10 features), similar covariance matrices across classes, no features with very low variance, and acceptable class balance (imbalance ratio of 1.61). However, critical issues were identified: none of the features follow a normal distribution (as evidenced by the Shapiro-Wilk test results with p-values below 0.05 for all features), and the dataset contains highly correlated features (correlation > 0.9). These violations undermine the assumptions of normality and independence required for LDA, indicating that the model may not perform reliably on this dataset. To address these issues, consider feature transformation (e.g., log or Box-Cox transformations) to improve normality, and use techniques like PCA to reduce multicollinearity. summry: The dataset is not currently suitable for Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA) due to the following issues:

  1. Non-Normality of Features: All features fail the normality test, violating LDA's assumption that features within each class are normally distributed.
  2. High Multicollinearity: Some features are highly correlated (correlation > 0.9), which violates the assumption of weakly correlated or independent features.

Feature selection¶

We want to choose the best features for our use case. We have learned 3 methods of Feature Selection:

  1. Forward Feature Selection
  2. Backward Feature Selection
  3. Hybrid Feature Selection

In Forward Feature Selection we start from one feature and add features (all combinations) until we reach the number of maximum features or until we reach the best score.

In Backward Feature Selection we start from the full feature set and remove features until we reach the number of minimum features or until we reach the best score (early stopping).

In Hybrid Feature Selection, we start from zero features and add/remove features until we reach the best score.

We will use Scikit-learn Recursive Feature Elimination (RFE) that is based on the Backward Feature Selection. Note: We will specify the target number of features to find and the selector will stop when it will reach this number of features.

Let's find the best n_features_to_select=3 features on our dataset.

We can use CV (Cross-Validation) instead of breaking the data to train-validation splits.

KPI AND Confusion Matrix¶

TP (True Positive) - The model classified correctly that a sample is positive. TN (True Negative) - The model classified correctly that a sample is negative. FP (False Positive) - The model classified a sample as positive but the sample is actually negative. FN (False Negative) - The model classified a sample as negative but the sample is actually positive.

Here's a short explanation of the KPIs:

  1. Accuracy: The proportion of correct predictions out of all predictions.

  1. False Positive Rate (FPR): The proportion of negative cases incorrectly classified as positive.

  2. Specificity: The proportion of actual negative cases correctly identified.

    • Formula: True NegativesTrue Negatives + False Positives\frac{\text{True Negatives}}{\text{True Negatives + False Positives}}

  3. Other KPIs:

    • Precision: Proportion of positive predictions that are correct.
    • Recall (Sensitivity): Proportion of actual positives correctly identified.
    • F1 Score: Harmonic mean of Precision and Recall.

These KPIs help evaluate model performance, especially in classification tasks.

Bootstrap Evaluation of Models Using Feature Selection Methods¶

Overview: This experiment evaluates the performance of Multinomial Naive Bayes (MultinomialNB) and K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN) classifiers using three feature selection methods: Backward Elimination, Forward Selection, and Hybrid Selection. Bootstrap sampling and bagging are applied to analyze the models' accuracy, log loss, and consistency over multiple iterations.

In [93]:
from sklearn.metrics import precision_score, recall_score, f1_score, confusion_matrix
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.metrics import log_loss, accuracy_score, ConfusionMatrixDisplay
from sklearn.ensemble import BaggingClassifier
from sklearn.naive_bayes import MultinomialNB
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.utils import resample
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler

# Feature selection methods
feature_selection_methods = ["Backward Elimination", "Forward Selection", "Hybrid Selection"]
dataframes = [X_selected_backword, X_selected_forward, X_selected_hybrid]

# Number of bootstrap iterations
n_iterations = 50

for feature_method, df, k in zip(feature_selection_methods, dataframes, optimal_k):
    print(f"\n{'=' * 40}\nFeature Selection Method: {feature_method}\n{'=' * 40}")
    X_NBC = MinMaxScaler().fit_transform(df)
    estimators = [
        ("MultinomialNB", MultinomialNB(), X_NBC),
        ("KNeighborsClassifier", KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k), df)
    ]
    for model_name, estimator, current_df in estimators:
        print(f"\n{'-' * 20}\nModel: {model_name}\n{'-' * 20}")
        print(f"Running bootstrap iterations for {model_name} with {feature_method}")

        # Accuracy and loss tracking
        train_accuracies = []
        val_accuracies = []
        train_losses = []
        val_losses = []

        # Bagging classifier
        bagging_model = BaggingClassifier(estimator=estimator,
                                          n_estimators=20, random_state=1,
                                          bootstrap=True)

        for iteration in range(n_iterations):
            # Resample for bootstrap
            X_train, t_train = resample(current_df, t, replace=True)
            X_val, t_val = resample(current_df, t, replace=False)

            # Train the model
            bagging_model.fit(X_train, t_train)

            # Compute accuracy for train and validation
            train_accuracy = accuracy_score(t_train, bagging_model.predict(X_train))
            train_accuracies.append(train_accuracy)

            val_accuracy = accuracy_score(t_val, bagging_model.predict(X_val))
            val_accuracies.append(val_accuracy)

            # Compute log loss for train and validation
            train_loss = log_loss(t_train, bagging_model.predict_proba(X_train))
            val_loss = log_loss(t_val, bagging_model.predict_proba(X_val))

            train_losses.append(train_loss)
            val_losses.append(val_loss)

        # Compute averages
        mean_train_accuracy = np.mean(train_accuracies)
        mean_val_accuracy = np.mean(val_accuracies)
        mean_train_loss = np.mean(train_losses)
        mean_val_loss = np.mean(val_losses)

        print(f"\nResults for {model_name} using {feature_method}:")
        print(f"Average Training Accuracy: {mean_train_accuracy:.4f}")
        print(f"Average Validation Accuracy: {mean_val_accuracy:.4f}")
        print(f"Average Training Loss (Log Loss): {mean_train_loss:.4f}")
        print(f"Average Validation Loss (Log Loss): {mean_val_loss:.4f}")

        # Calculate KPIs for the training and validation sets
        def calculate_kpis(true_labels, predictions):
            cm = confusion_matrix(true_labels, predictions)
            tp = cm[1, 1]  # True Positives
            tn = cm[0, 0]  # True Negatives
            fp = cm[0, 1]  # False Positives
            fn = cm[1, 0]  # False Negatives

            # Precision, Recall, F1-Score
            precision = precision_score(true_labels, predictions)
            recall = recall_score(true_labels, predictions)
            f1 = f1_score(true_labels, predictions)

            # Specificity and False Positive Rate
            specificity = tn / (tn + fp) if (tn + fp) != 0 else 0
            fpr = fp / (fp + tn) if (fp + tn) != 0 else 0

            return precision, recall, f1, specificity, fpr

        # Train KPIs
        train_predictions = bagging_model.predict(X_train)
        train_precision, train_recall, train_f1, train_specificity, train_fpr = calculate_kpis(t_train, train_predictions)
        print(f"\nTraining KPIs for {model_name} using {feature_method}:")
        print(f"Precision: {train_precision:.4f}")
        print(f"Recall: {train_recall:.4f}")
        print(f"F1 Score: {train_f1:.4f}")
        print(f"Specificity: {train_specificity:.4f}")
        print(f"False Positive Rate: {train_fpr:.4f}")

        # Validation KPIs
        val_predictions = bagging_model.predict(X_val)
        val_precision, val_recall, val_f1, val_specificity, val_fpr = calculate_kpis(t_val, val_predictions)
        print(f"\nValidation KPIs for {model_name} using {feature_method}:")
        print(f"Precision: {val_precision:.4f}")
        print(f"Recall: {val_recall:.4f}")
        print(f"F1 Score: {val_f1:.4f}")
        print(f"Specificity: {val_specificity:.4f}")
        print(f"False Positive Rate: {val_fpr:.4f}")

        # Plot training vs validation accuracy
        plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
        plt.plot(train_accuracies, label="Training Accuracy")
        plt.plot(val_accuracies, label="Validation Accuracy")
        plt.xlabel('Bootstrap Iterations')
        plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
        plt.legend()
        plt.title(f'{model_name} - Training vs Validation Accuracy ({feature_method})')
        plt.show()

        # Plot training vs validation loss
        plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
        plt.plot(train_losses, label="Training Loss")
        plt.plot(val_losses, label="Validation Loss")
        plt.xlabel('Bootstrap Iterations')
        plt.ylabel('Loss')
        plt.legend()
        plt.title(f'{model_name} - Training vs Validation Loss ({feature_method})')
        plt.show()

        # Confusion matrices
        train_cm = confusion_matrix(t_train, train_predictions)
        ConfusionMatrixDisplay(confusion_matrix=train_cm).plot()
        plt.title(f'{model_name} - Training Confusion Matrix ({feature_method})')
        plt.show()

        val_cm = confusion_matrix(t_val, val_predictions)
        ConfusionMatrixDisplay(confusion_matrix=val_cm).plot()
        plt.title(f'{model_name} - Validation Confusion Matrix ({feature_method})')
        plt.show()

tested three feature selection methods: Backward Elimination, Forward Selection, and Hybrid Selection. For each method, evaluated two models: MultinomialNB (Naive Bayes) and KNeighborsClassifier (KNN). The output provides several performance metrics for both models across different bootstrap iterations.

Model Performance:¶

  1. Training and Validation Accuracy:

    • Accuracy measures how many correct predictions are made. A higher accuracy means the model is doing well.
      • Backward Elimination: KNeighborsClassifier (Training: 0.8462, Validation: 0.8250) had better accuracy than MultinomialNB (Training: 0.7893, Validation: 0.7881).
      • Forward Selection: KNeighborsClassifier (Training: 0.8116, Validation: 0.8041) performed better than MultinomialNB (Training: 0.7874, Validation: 0.7868).
      • Hybrid Selection: KNeighborsClassifier (Training: 0.8095, Validation: 0.8031) had better performance than MultinomialNB (Training: 0.7914, Validation: 0.7855).

  2. Log Loss:

    • Log Loss indicates how confident the model is in its predictions (lower is better). A lower log loss means the model's probability estimates are closer to the actual labels.
      • Backward Elimination: KNeighborsClassifier (Training: 0.3369, Validation: 0.6123) had a lower log loss than MultinomialNB (Training: 0.4829, Validation: 0.4872).
      • Forward Selection: KNeighborsClassifier (Training: 0.4202, Validation: 0.4961) had lower log loss than MultinomialNB (Training: 0.4995, Validation: 0.5025).
      • Hybrid Selection: KNeighborsClassifier (Training: 0.4201, Validation: 0.5104) had a lower log loss than MultinomialNB (Training: 0.5085, Validation: 0.5135).

KPIs (Key Performance Indicators):¶

These metrics give deeper insights into how well the models perform on different types of predictions:

  1. Precision: The proportion of true positives among all positive predictions (higher is better).

    • For MultinomialNB, Hybrid Selection had a much higher precision (Training: 0.9577, Validation: 0.9471), indicating the model is more likely to classify positives correctly.
    • For KNeighborsClassifier, Hybrid Selection also performed well in precision (Training: 0.8497, Validation: 0.7744).

  2. Recall: The proportion of true positives correctly identified out of all actual positives (higher is better).

    • KNeighborsClassifier with Hybrid Selection had the highest recall (Training: 0.7406, Validation: 0.6725), meaning it identified a higher proportion of actual positive cases.
    • MultinomialNB with Hybrid Selection had a lower recall (Training: 0.4488, Validation: 0.4708).

  3. F1 Score: A harmonic mean of precision and recall, providing a balance between the two (higher is better).

    • KNeighborsClassifier with Hybrid Selection had the highest F1 score (Training: 0.7914, Validation: 0.7199).
    • MultinomialNB with Hybrid Selection had a moderate F1 score (Training: 0.6112, Validation: 0.6289).

  4. Specificity: The proportion of true negatives correctly identified (higher is better).

    • KNeighborsClassifier with Hybrid Selection had the highest specificity (Training: 0.9052, Validation: 0.8780), meaning it is better at identifying negative cases.
    • MultinomialNB with Hybrid Selection had very high specificity (Training: 0.9898, Validation: 0.9836), suggesting it performed well in identifying negatives but at the cost of lower recall.

  5. False Positive Rate (FPR): The proportion of negative cases incorrectly classified as positive (lower is better).

    • KNeighborsClassifier with Hybrid Selection had the lowest FPR (Training: 0.0833, Validation: 0.1056), indicating it made fewer false positive errors.
    • MultinomialNB with Hybrid Selection had a low FPR as well (Training: 0.0102, Validation: 0.0164).

Summary:¶

  • KNeighborsClassifier generally outperformed MultinomialNB across feature selection methods in terms of accuracy and log loss.

  • Precision and Recall provide insight into how well the models are balancing their prediction of positive and negative cases. MultinomialNB had high precision but lower recall, especially with Hybrid Selection.

  • KNeighborsClassifier with Hybrid Selection showed the best balance of KPIs with the highest F1 score, specificity, and low false positive rate.

summary for each model:

For KNN, the performance heavily relies on the notion of local similarity and the distribution of data in the feature space. If the dataset has noisy features, irrelevant features, or an uneven class distribution, the nearest neighbors might not accurately represent the true relationship between the data points. Furthermore, if the feature scaling is inconsistent or the dataset is high-dimensional, the "curse of dimensionality" can degrade the model's performance, making distances between points less meaningful and reducing the model's ability to correctly classify samples.

For NBC, the model assumes that features are conditionally independent given the class label. This "naive" assumption often does not hold in real-world datasets, where features may exhibit complex correlations. Additionally, NBC works best with categorical data or data that can be discretized meaningfully. If your features are continuous and their distributions deviate significantly from the assumed multinomial or Gaussian distribution (depending on the variant), the model's probability estimates become less reliable. These mismatches can lead to poor generalization on the validation set and high log error.

The gap in validation performance for both models might indicate issues with feature quality, preprocessing (e.g., scaling, encoding, or feature selection), or class imbalance. Further analysis, such as checking feature importance, exploring correlations, and experimenting with data transformations, could provide insights into mitigating these errors.

Regularization¶

Laso, Ridge and Elastic Regularization on Logistic Regression

High-Variance could be decresed using Regularizations. With regularization, we can control the size of the model weights and thus reduce the variance. We control the size of the model weights by adding a negative term to the loss function. This term is called a penalty to high weights.

We have learned about three regularization techniques:

  1. L1 (also called Lasso).
  2. L2 (also called Ridge).
  3. Elastic Net (a combination of Lasso and Ridge).

We can use these regularizations as Hyper-Parameters in Scikit-learn SGDClassifier.

In [96]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression

from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

# Cross-validation for Ridge regularization

# Cross-validation for ElasticNet regularization
elastic_score = cross_val_score(make_pipeline(StandardScaler(), lr_elastic_cls), X_encoded, t, cv=15).mean()
print(f'sgd_elastic: {elastic_score}')

We choose: ElasticNet outperforms the other two by a small margin. All three regularizations perform similarly, with ElasticNet slightly better, suggesting it combines the strengths of both Lasso and Ridge regularizations for this dataset.

from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, precision_score, recall_score, f1_score, confusion_matrix, log_loss
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
import numpy as np

# Initialize Logistic Regression
logreg = LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000, random_state=1)

# Lists to store training and validation losses
train_losses = []
val_losses = []
training_sizes = np.linspace(0.1, 1.0, 10)  # Incremental training sizes

# Train model incrementally and calculate log loss
for size in training_sizes:
    # Sample a fraction of the training data
    X_train_sampled, t_train_sampled = X_train[:int(size * len(X_train))], t_train[:int(size * len(t_train))]

    # Train the model
    logreg.fit(X_train_sampled, t_train_sampled)

    # Predict probabilities
    t_pred_train_proba = logreg.predict_proba(X_train_sampled)
    t_pred_val_proba = logreg.predict_proba(X_val)

    # Calculate log loss for training and validation
    train_loss = log_loss(t_train_sampled, t_pred_train_proba)
    val_loss = log_loss(t_val, t_pred_val_proba)

    # Append losses
    train_losses.append(train_loss)
    val_losses.append(val_loss)

# Plot validation loss vs training loss
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(training_sizes, train_losses, label='Training Loss', marker='o')
plt.plot(training_sizes, val_losses, label='Validation Loss', marker='s')
plt.title("Training vs Validation Loss", fontsize=18)
plt.xlabel("Fraction of Training Data", fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel("Log Loss", fontsize=14)
plt.legend(fontsize=12)
plt.grid(alpha=0.3)
plt.show()

The results show a typical pattern where the log loss on the training data decreases as the fraction of training data increases, which is expected because the model has more data to learn from. However, the log loss on the validation set stabilizes around 0.48, indicating that the model's ability to generalize does not improve significantly with more training data beyond a certain point. This suggests that the model might be overfitting the training data as it becomes more specialized, while its performance on the validation set remains relatively constant.

# calculate precision, recall, specificity, fpr and accuracy
def precision(cm):
    tn, fp, fn, tp = cm.ravel()
    return tp/(tp+fp)

def recall(cm):
    tn, fp, fn, tp = cm.ravel()
    return tp/(tp+fn)

def specificity(cm):
    tn, fp, fn, tp = cm.ravel()
    return tn/(tn+fp)

def fpr(cm):
    tn, fp, fn, tp = cm.ravel()
    return fp/(fp+tn)

def accuracy(cm):
    tn, fp, fn, tp = cm.ravel()
    return (tp+tn)/(tp+tn+fp+fn)

print(f'Train: precision {precision(cm_train):.2f}, recall {recall(cm_train):.2f}, specificity {specificity(cm_train):.2f}, fpr {fpr(cm_train):.2f}, accuracy {accuracy(cm_train):.2f}')
print(f'Val:   precision {precision(cm_val):.2f}, recall {recall(cm_val):.2f}, specificity {specificity(cm_val):.2f}, fpr {fpr(cm_val):.2f}, accuracy {accuracy(cm_val):.2f}')

Train: precision 0.74, recall 0.71, specificity 0.85, fpr 0.15, accuracy 0.80
Val:   precision 0.76, recall 0.70, specificity 0.85, fpr 0.15, accuracy 0.79

# calculate f1 and balanced accuracy
def f1(cm):
    precision_calc = precision(cm)
    recall_calc = recall(cm)
    return (2*precision_calc*recall_calc)/(precision_calc+recall_calc)

def balanced_accuracy(cm):
    recall_calc = recall(cm)
    specificity_calc = specificity(cm)
    return (recall_calc+specificity_calc)/2

print(f'Train: f1 {f1(cm_train):.2f}, balanced_accuracy {balanced_accuracy(cm_train):.2f}')
print(f'Val:   f1 {f1(cm_val):.2f}, balanced_accuracy {balanced_accuracy(cm_val):.2f}')

In [108]:
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.utils import resample
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np

# Assuming `X_selected_hybrid` contains the selected features after feature selection
selected_features = X_selected_hybrid.columns

# Ensure both training and test datasets contain the same selected features
X_train_KNN = X_train_KNN[selected_features]
test_df_encoded_KNN = test_df_encoded_KNN[selected_features]



# Set up KNN model
k = 5  # Adjust the number of neighbors for KNN
knn_model = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k)

# Initialize an empty list to store predictions from bootstrap iterations
predictions_list = []

# Number of bootstrap iterations
n_iterations = 50

# Train the model using bootstrap sampling and make predictions
for i in range(n_iterations):
    # Resample the training data with replacement (Bootstrap sampling)
    X_train_KNN_resampled, t_train_resampled = resample(X_train_KNN, t_train, replace=True, random_state=i)
    
    # Standardize the features using StandardScaler
    scaler = StandardScaler()
    X_train_KNN_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_train_KNN_resampled)
    test_scaled = scaler.transform(test_df_encoded_KNN)  # Apply the same transformation to the test data

    # Train the KNN model
    knn_model.fit(X_train_KNN_scaled, t_train_resampled)
    
    # Make predictions on the test set
    predictions = knn_model.predict(test_scaled)
    predictions_list.append(predictions)

# Calculate the average prediction (for ensemble effect)
final_predictions = np.mean(predictions_list, axis=0)  # Average predictions from all iterations
final_predictions = np.round(final_predictions).astype(int)  # Convert to binary class (0 or 1)

# Create the submission file
output = pd.DataFrame({'PassengerId': id_test,  # Ensure `id_test` contains PassengerId from the test set
                       'Survived': final_predictions})

output.to_csv('submission_knn_bootstrap.csv', index=False)

print("Saved the predictions to a .csv file using KNN with bootstrap sampling.")

Saved the predictions to a .csv file using KNN with bootstrap sampling.

Summary of the Work¶

1. Data Investigation and Preprocessing¶

  • Data Analysis: Initial exploration included understanding the dataset structure, examining missing values, and identifying categorical and numerical features.
  • Feature Encoding:
    • Categorical variables like Embarked and Sex were one-hot encoded.
  • Handling Missing Values: Imputation techniques were applied for missing data.

2. Feature Selection¶

using RFE and RFECV

Forward Feature Selection Backward Feature Selection Hybrid Feature Selection

  • Selected features included:
    • Categorical: Embarked_C, Embarked_Q, Embarked_S, Sex_female, Sex_male, Pclass.
    • Numerical: Age, SibSp, Fare.
  • Dropped irrelevant or redundant features after analyzing correlations and importance.

3. Data Splitting and Cross-Validation¶

  • Data Splitting:
    • Data was split into training (80%) and validation (20%) sets using train_test_split.
  • Cross-Validation: Incremental training sizes were used to evaluate the model's robustness and learning curve, comparing training and validation log loss.

Bootstrapping

4. Normalization and Regularization¶

  • Feature Normalization: Applied StandardScaler to normalize features.
  • Regularization: Elastic net regularization was used in the logistic regression model to balance L1 (sparsity) and L2 (ridge-like penalties).
    • The optimal balance (l1_ratio = 0.5) was chosen to prevent overfitting and improve generalization.

5. Model Training and Evaluation¶

  • Pipeline: A pipeline with ordinal encoding, feature scaling, and logistic regression was created for efficient modeling.
  • Metrics Evaluated:
    • Precision, recall, F1 score, specificity, false positive rate (FPR), accuracy, balanced accuracy.
    • Training and validation confusion matrices were computed and analyzed.

KNN NBC LDA- undersdanding and investigating

6. Results and Observations¶

  • The model achieved consistent performance between training and validation sets, demonstrating good generalization.
    • Training F1: 0.73, Validation F1: 0.73.
    • Balanced Accuracy (Validation): 0.77.
  • The learning curve showed that the model performed consistently across different fractions of training data.

7. Competition Outcome¶

  • The model achieved a real test score of 0.77511 in the competition, indicating strong predictive performance and ranking competitively.
  • Place: 7409

Key Takeaways¶

  • Effective preprocessing, feature engineering, and model tuning led to a well-performing logistic regression model.
  • Elastic net regularization and feature scaling ensured robustness and reduced overfitting.
  • Consistent validation results highlighted the model's ability to generalize to unseen data.
